From: AGX team
Subject: [PATCH] htree-init: zero the full block, not just the root struct

ext4_dir_dx_init() partial-memsets the htree root struct (~32 bytes)
inside a freshly-allocated 4 KiB buffer that comes from
ext4_trans_block_get_noread().  The buffer cache hands back
uninitialised heap memory, so the htree padding (bytes past the
root struct, before the dx_entry array fills) goes to disk
verbatim, carrying stale bytes.

That makes the on-disk image non-deterministic across identical
mounts and also leaks heap contents into the persistent filesystem.
Zeroing the full block before writing the dot entries / climit
costs one extra 4 KiB memset per directory and closes both
issues.

Regression test: crates/oci-converter/tests/ext4_determinism.rs
(currently ignored — more partial-memsets remain in lwext4).

---
 src/ext4_dir_idx.c | 9 ++++++++-
 1 file changed, 8 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/src/ext4_dir_idx.c b/src/ext4_dir_idx.c
--- a/src/ext4_dir_idx.c
+++ b/src/ext4_dir_idx.c
@@ -377,7 +377,14 @@ int ext4_dir_dx_init(struct ext4_inode_ref *dir, struct ext4_inode_ref *parent)
 	struct ext4_dir_idx_root *root = (void *)block.data;
 	struct ext4_dir_idx_rinfo *info = &(root->info);

-	memset(root, 0, sizeof(struct ext4_dir_idx_root));
+	/* Zero the whole block, not just the header. The buffer
+	 * returned by ext4_trans_block_get_noread is uninitialised
+	 * heap memory; the htree padding after the dot entries and
+	 * the climit/info structs would otherwise carry stale
+	 * bytes into the on-disk image. That makes the output
+	 * non-deterministic across identical converts — see AGX
+	 * T3-3 regression in `tests/ext4_determinism.rs`. */
+	memset(root, 0, block_size);
 	struct ext4_dir_en *de;

 	/* Initialize dot entries */
